<h1>Example 1</h1>

	<section>
		<p class="example-intro">Two of the most commonly confused words are <b>affect</b> and <b>effect</b>. They may sound similar, but they actually mean very different things. <b>Affect</b> is a <i>verb</i> that means "to influence". <b>Effect</b> is a <i>noun</i> that means "result". One trick to keeping these two straight is to remember that affect is an action (they both start with A's!) while effect is a thing.</p>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The <span class="red">affects</span> of the treatment were more positive than the team had originally hoped for.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here we see affects being used as a noun instead of a verb. Remember, affects with an "a" is always an action.</p>
		<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The <span class="green">effects</span> of the treatment were more positive than the team had originally hoped for.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Now we're looking better! We've replaced the verb "affects" with the noun "effects", and corrected the sentence.</p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">Doctors and nurses both must be aware of how their actions <span class="red">effect</span> patient quality of life.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">In this example we see effect being used as an action, which is incorrect.</p>
		<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">Doctors and nurses both must be aware of how their actions <span class="green">affect</span> patient quality of life.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The sentence is corrected by replacing the noun "effect" with the verb "affect".</p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

