<h1>Example 2</h1>

	<section>
		<p class="example-intro">Another set of commonly confused words are <b>insure</b>, <b>ensure</b> and <b>assure</b>. Because they are all verbs, part of speech won't help us determine which is correct, so we'll just need to remember the different meanings of each. To <b>insure</b> means "to protect against loss", to <b>ensure</b> means "to make certain", and to <b>assure</b> means "to give confidence". There aren't really any shortcuts here, you'll just have to commit them to memory! Check out the following examples. </p>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">It's up to every person in a healthcare environment to <span class="red">insure</span> that each patient gets the best care possible.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">At first glance you might think this one is correct, but be careful! What is the action being taken in this sentence? Aren't we trying to <i>make certain</i> that each patient gets the best care possible?</p>
		<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">It's up to every person in a healthcare environment to <span class="green">ensure</span> that each patient gets the best care possible.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">That's more like it! Remember, to <b>insure</b> means to protect something against loss, whereas to <b>ensure</b> means to make certain of something.</p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">There are a number of companies that <span class="red">ensure</span> patients' healthcare costs.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is talking about a financial insurance policy, so the correct word is "insure"</p>
		<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">There are a number of companies that <span class="green">insure</span> patients' healthcare costs.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">To correct the sentence, we replace "ensure" with "insure". Remember to keep your "i" on your money!</p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The veteran nurse took the time to <span class="red">ensure</span> the newer nurses that they would learn to adapt to and thrive in the hospital's chaos, and that every nurse had experienced what they were now experiencing.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence incorrectly uses "ensure' in place of "assure". Remember that "assure" should be used in situations where the subject is trying to relieve another's doubts or assert something positively.</p>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-corrected">The veteran nurse took the time to <span class="red">ensure</span> the newer nurses that they would learn to adapt to and thrive in the hospital's chaos, and that every nurse had experienced what they were now experiencing.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The sentence is corrected by replacing "ensure" with "assure".</p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

