<h1>Example 3</h1>

	<section>
		<p class="example-intro">Next up on our list of commonly confused words, "principal" and "principle". Easily confused due to identical pronounciations, the two actually serve very different roles and have very different meanings. "Principal" is an adjective that is used to designate something as primary, or chief, or first-order, whereas "principle" is a noun that means a standard or value. Here's a few examples of how the confusion occurs.</p>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">Because of their proximity and the frequency of their visits, nurses will often become a patient's <span class="red">principle</span> resource.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence uses "principle" incorrectly. Instead of being used correctly as a noun, it is attached as an adjective to "resource". The role of adjective is served by "principal".</p>
		<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">Because of their proximity and the frequency of their visits, nurses will often become a patient's <span class="green">principal</span> resource.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Switch the two out, and the sentence is all cleaned up. If it's an adjective, use "principal" with an "a", if it's a noun, use "principle" with an "e". </p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">Providing healthcare is an important and sensitive service, and all practitioners must hold themselves to certain ethical <span class="red">principals</span>.</h4>
		<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence is the reverse of the above example. Here we use "principal" as a noun instead of an adjective. When we are talking about standards or values we are talking about "principles", not "principal".</p>
		<h4 class="example example-sentence example-corrected">Providing healthcare is an important and sensitive service, and all practitioners must hold themselves to certain ethical <span class="green">principles</span>.</h4>
		<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Switch the two out, and the sentence is all cleaned up. If it's an adjective, use "principal" with an "a", if it's a noun, use "principle" with an "e". </p>
		<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
	</section>
